lenders.occupational_info:
Tips on Buying Large Displacement Dodge and Ford Engines

There is a lot to love about the diesel engines in our trucks, but its longevity is perhaps that which we love most. After all, longevity along with fuel performance and torque are the primary reasons we opted for diesel in the first place. Nevertheless, our diesel engine won’t last forever, and the only alternative to buying new is replacing it with a used engine.

The upside to that is since diesels are long lasting, they provide great value as used engines. This is particularly true in the case of Dodge engines and Ford engines. However, the downside is that buying used large displacement Dodge and Ford engines can be tricky business. In order to help you avoid the perils and make the right choice among all those Ford and Dodge engines, we’ve compiled this list of tips.

1. Know precisely what you need. The sheer amount of information available concerning used diesel Dodge and Ford engines will overwhelm you if you go into this process unprepared. The key is to focus just on the relevant information.

2. Avoid buying Dodge engines or any other brand through an individual seller. End-of-life diesels can be problematic, and it is vital to buy one with a reasonable amount of mileage, and to get assurance that the mileage number is accurate.

3. It is easy to lie about mileage when it comes to selling an engine. Therefore, it is vital that you verify the mileage using the appropriate vehicle history reports from one or more of the reputable services. The premier dealers who sell used Dodge and Ford engines will offer this service to their clients free.

4. Research with the target mileage in mind. You’ll have plenty of options if you’re buying an engine with 100-150K miles. However, if you plan buy to one with 300K, make certain of the target engine’s reputation at that mileage.

5. The common length of a used engine warranty in the industry is only six months. However, because of the durability of diesel Ford and Dodge engines, it is possible to get 1- and 2-year guarantees. Do not settle for less than a 1-year warranty.

6. After you checked the records, it is time to do a cursory examination of the engine. Determine the problem areas on this specific engine and examine those spots. However, don’t settle with a personal examination.

7. Hire a professional mechanic to inspect the engine before purchase. If you are paying an engine shop to install the engine, they will normally include this service. If the dealer and the shop are one in the same, hire a mechanic from an outside source.

8. Buying online is viable as long as you are adhering to the other steps. You will find some amazing deals, but remember to factor in freight shipping in order to get an accurate assessment. Companies that sell engines online provide the same guarantees of mileage and condition you’d expect from a local shop.

The most important aspect of this process is utilizing as much patience as is possible. Time is a luxury, but use as much of it as you have in order to follow the steps outlined above and to do the necessary research. Doing so won’t guarantee you an easy time, but it should ensure a successful used diesel engine purchase.
